Another argument, which is almost conclusive, can be drawn from the development in the structure of the elegiae couplet, and especially of the pentameter, whichcan be traced in the poems as they stand. In Books l and II Propertius constantly ends his pentameters with words of three, four, and five syllables: the number of such end· ings is far rarer in Book 111, and ceases almost entirely in Book IV: in seven out of the eleven poems of that book not one of these endings occur.
